        "text": "Solutions to the 64th William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition Saturday, December 6, 2003",
        "bbox": [
          0.1992156862745098,
          0.06363636363636363,
          0.807843137254902,
          0.1
        ],
        "order": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_1",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Manjul Bhargava, Kiran Kedaya, and Lenny Ng",
        "bbox": [
          0.3349019607843137,
          0.11393939393939394,
          0.6713725490196079,
          0.1290909090909091
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A1 There are n such sums. More precisely, there is exactly one such sum with k terms for each of k = 1, . ., n (and clearly no others). To see this, note that if n = a1 + a2 + .  · + ak with a1 ≤ a2 ≤ · · ≤ ak ≤ a1 + 1, then",
        "bbox": [
          0.1011764705882353,
          0.16484848484848486,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.22424242424242424
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Third solution: Since both sides are continuous in each ai, it is sufficient to prove the claim with a1 , . . , an all positive (the general case follows by taking limits as some of the ai tend to zero). Put ri = bi/ai; then the given inequality is equivalent to",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.16484848484848486,
          0.92,
          0.2381818181818182
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In terms of the function",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.2793939393939394,
          0.7152941176470589,
          0.29333333333333333
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "However, there is a unique integer a1 satisfying these inequalities, namely a1 = |n/k. Moreover, once a1 is fixed, there are k different possibilities for the sum a1 + a2 + …  + ak: if i is the last integer such that ai = a1, then the sum equals ka1 + (i – 1). The possible values of i are 1, ., , and exactly one of these sums comes out equal to n, proving our claim.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12627450980392158,
          0.29818181818181816,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.4012121212121212
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "and the quantities si = log ri, we can rewrite the desired inequality as",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.3333333333333333,
          0.92,
          0.3624242424242424
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note: In summary, there is a unique partition of n with k terms that is \"as equally spaced as possible\". One can also obtain essentially the same construction induc- tively: except for the all-ones sum, each partition of n is obtained by \"augmenting\" a unique partition of n – 1.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12549019607843137,
          0.40545454545454546,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.47878787878787876
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_13",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "This will follow from Jensen's inequality if we can ver- ify that f is a convex function; it is enough to check that f (x) > 0 for all x. In fact,",
        "bbox": [
          0.5552941176470588,
          0.4163636363636364,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.46060606060606063
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0002",
